It was more a question of why aren't we doing something like this instead.
```
} finally {
  try {
    curScope.close
  } catch {
    case closeThrowable: Throwable =>
      if (NonFatal(retThrowable) && !NonFatal(closeThrowable))
        retThrowable = closeThrowable
      else safeAddSuppressed(retThrowable, closeThrowable)
   } finally {
     throw retThrowable
   }
}
```
We call curScope.close regardless of the value of retThrowable so I don't think we need the if. NonFatal(null) returns true so the check to see which to throw should still work. I don't think you need the var toThrow because retThrowable can just be overwritten in the if statement if you decide to throw closeThrowable instead.

I'm on the fence here about whether we should just throw the first exception and not the most fatal exception. My intuition says that the first exception will almost certainly be causing the 2nd regardless of which is fatal.

